const v20ReadA={id:"v20-read-a",kind:"passage",label:"Passage for Items 69-72",title:"Appointment Window Trial",description:"A permit office replaced one undifferentiated queue with appointment windows while reserving some daily capacity for walk-ins. Average waiting time fell during the six-week trial, but walk-in waits rose on days when scheduled slots were nearly full. Some appointment holders did not arrive, leaving capacity unused until staff manually reassigned it. Analysts proposed releasing an unused slot after a stated grace period and reporting appointment and walk-in outcomes separately. They also cautioned that a lower average wait would not by itself prove better service unless completion, abandonment, repeat visits, and the mix of applicants were tracked.",alt:"Passage about an appointment-window trial that lowered average waiting time but sometimes lengthened walk-in waits, with unused no-show slots and a recommendation to track separate service outcomes."};
const v20ReadB={id:"v20-read-b",kind:"passage",label:"Babasahin para sa Aytem 73-76",title:"Mapa ng Daluyan",description:"Gumawa ang mga residente ng digital na mapa ng baradong kanal at mababang bahagi ng kalsada. Ang bawat ulat ay may larawan, oras, at lokasyon. Nakatulong ang mapa sa pag-una sa paglilinis, ngunit mas maraming ulat ang nagmula sa lugar na mas malakas ang internet at mas aktibo ang mga volunteer. Kaya nagsagawa rin ang inhinyero ng regular na inspeksiyon sa mga lugar na kakaunti ang ulat. Inihambing nila ang ulat, aktuwal na bara, lalim ng baha, at oras ng paglinis. Ginamit ang mapa bilang gabay, hindi bilang patunay na ligtas ang lugar na walang ulat.",alt:"Teksto tungkol sa citizen flood-drain map na may larawan, oras, at lokasyon, ngunit may reporting bias kaya dinagdagan ng regular na inspeksiyon at paghahambing sa aktuwal na bara at baha."};
const v20ReadC={id:"v20-read-c",kind:"passage",label:"Passage for Items 77-80",title:"Repair-or-Replace Analysis",description:"A school division considered replacing laptops after repair spending increased. The oldest units had low purchase prices, but several lacked security support and stayed out of service while parts were ordered. Analysts compared remaining useful life, repair probability, downtime, energy use, software support, resale value, and staff retraining. A pilot assigned comparable offices either refurbished units or new units and recorded service interruptions for a year. Managers noted that choosing only the most damaged offices for one option would bias the comparison, and that the least expensive initial purchase might not have the lowest total cost.",alt:"Passage about comparing laptop repair, refurbishment, and replacement through lifecycle cost, support, downtime, and a fair pilot rather than initial price alone."};
